{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Neural Networks for Time Series\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.hero}\n",
        "**Part VI. Deep Learning for Time Series and Sequence Data**  \n",
        "**Chapter goal:** build the first deep-learning forecasting model for time series by converting ordered observations into supervised learning examples. We study sliding windows, neural-network maps, loss functions, backpropagation, regularization, leakage-aware validation, and AI-assisted model critique.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Learning objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "After studying this chapter, you should be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. convert a univariate or multivariate time series into input-label windows;\n",
        "2. distinguish sequence-to-one, sequence-to-sequence, recursive, direct, and multi-output neural forecasts;\n",
        "3. define a neural forecasting model as a nonlinear map $f_\\theta$ from a history window to a future horizon;\n",
        "4. formulate empirical risk minimization for time-series forecasting;\n",
        "5. explain how backpropagation computes gradients through a computational graph;\n",
        "6. train a window-based multilayer perceptron while avoiding time leakage;\n",
        "7. compare a neural forecast with naive and linear baselines;\n",
        "8. diagnose overfitting using training and validation loss curves;\n",
        "9. explain why scaling, chronological splitting, and baselines are essential;\n",
        "10. use AI tools to critique the modeling workflow while verifying the mathematics and code independently.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.1 From classical forecasts to neural sequence maps\n",
        "\n",
        "Classical models in earlier chapters describe the current observation using explicit stochastic structure. For example, an AR($p$) model has the form\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Y_t = \\phi_1Y_{t-1}+\\cdots+\\phi_pY_{t-p}+W_t.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The one-step conditional mean is linear in the past:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbb E[Y_t\\mid Y_{t-1},\\ldots,Y_{t-p}]\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\phi_1Y_{t-1}+\\cdots+\\phi_pY_{t-p}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "A neural time-series model keeps the forecasting viewpoint but replaces the explicit linear map by a learned nonlinear map. Given a history window\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf x_t=(Y_{t-L+1},Y_{t-L+2},\\ldots,Y_t)\\in\\mathbb R^L,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and a forecasting horizon $H$, the target vector is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf y_t=(Y_{t+1},Y_{t+2},\\ldots,Y_{t+H})\\in\\mathbb R^H.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "A neural forecasting model is a parameterized function\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_\\theta:\\mathbb R^L\\to\\mathbb R^H,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\widehat{\\mathbf y}_t=f_\\theta(\\mathbf x_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This framework generalizes the AR model. If $H=1$ and $f_\\theta$ is linear, then the model is essentially an autoregression estimated by supervised learning. If $f_\\theta$ is a multilayer neural network, it can learn nonlinear interactions among lags.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Neural forecasting is still forecasting\n",
        "Deep learning does not remove the need for time-series thinking. We still need baselines, chronological validation, horizon-specific error analysis, and diagnostics for failures.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.2 Time-series windows as supervised learning data\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose we observe a sequence\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Y_1,Y_2,\\ldots,Y_T.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Choose an input length $L$ and forecast horizon $H$. For each feasible forecast origin $t$, construct\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf x_t=(Y_{t-L+1},\\ldots,Y_t)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf y_t=(Y_{t+1},\\ldots,Y_{t+H}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The resulting supervised data set is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathcal D\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\{(\\mathbf x_t,\\mathbf y_t):L\\le t\\le T-H\\}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently, the design matrix has rows\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X=\n",
        "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
        "Y_1 & Y_2 & \\cdots & Y_L\\\\\n",
        "Y_2 & Y_3 & \\cdots & Y_{L+1}\\\\\n",
        "\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots\\\\\n",
        "Y_{T-L-H+1} & Y_{T-L-H+2} & \\cdots & Y_{T-H}\n",
        "\\end{bmatrix},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and the target matrix is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Z=\n",
        "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
        "Y_{L+1} & Y_{L+2} & \\cdots & Y_{L+H}\\\\\n",
        "Y_{L+2} & Y_{L+3} & \\cdots & Y_{L+H+1}\\\\\n",
        "\\vdots & \\vdots & \\ddots & \\vdots\\\\\n",
        "Y_{T-H+1} & Y_{T-H+2} & \\cdots & Y_T\n",
        "\\end{bmatrix}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Each row is one supervised example. The row order is temporal and must be respected during validation.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Sequence-to-one and sequence-to-sequence\n",
        "\n",
        "A **sequence-to-one** model uses a history window to forecast one future value:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_\\theta:\\mathbb R^L\\to\\mathbb R,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\widehat Y_{t+1}=f_\\theta(Y_{t-L+1},\\ldots,Y_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "A **sequence-to-sequence** or **multi-output** model forecasts several future values at once:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_\\theta:\\mathbb R^L\\to\\mathbb R^H,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "(\\widehat Y_{t+1},\\ldots,\\widehat Y_{t+H})=f_\\theta(\\mathbf x_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For multivariate time series $\\mathbf Y_t\\in\\mathbb R^d$, the input window is a matrix\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf X_t=\n",
        "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
        "\\mathbf Y_{t-L+1}^\\top\\\\\n",
        "\\mathbf Y_{t-L+2}^\\top\\\\\n",
        "\\vdots\\\\\n",
        "\\mathbf Y_t^\\top\n",
        "\\end{bmatrix}\n",
        "\\in\\mathbb R^{L\\times d}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "An MLP usually flattens this matrix into a vector in $\\mathbb R^{Ld}$. Later chapters will preserve the temporal geometry using convolutional, recurrent, and attention-based architectures.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.3 Direct, recursive, and multi-output neural forecasts\n",
        "\n",
        "There are several ways to forecast multiple steps ahead.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Recursive one-step strategy\n",
        "\n",
        "Train a one-step model\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat Y_{t+1}=f_\\theta(Y_{t-L+1},\\ldots,Y_t),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then feed its own forecast back into the input window:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat Y_{t+2}=f_\\theta(Y_{t-L+2},\\ldots,Y_t,\\widehat Y_{t+1}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is simple, but errors can accumulate.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Direct strategy\n",
        "\n",
        "Train a separate model for each horizon:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat Y_{t+h}=f_{\\theta_h}^{(h)}(Y_{t-L+1},\\ldots,Y_t),\n",
        "\\qquad h=1,\\ldots,H.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This avoids recursive error propagation but requires fitting $H$ models.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Multi-output strategy\n",
        "\n",
        "Train one model that outputs all horizons simultaneously:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "(\\widehat Y_{t+1},\\ldots,\\widehat Y_{t+H})\n",
        "=\n",
        "f_\\theta(Y_{t-L+1},\\ldots,Y_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the strategy used in the main Python example below. It encourages the model to learn a coherent future path.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.theorem-box}\n",
        "## Neural networks as nonlinear autoregressions\n",
        "A window-based neural forecast can be viewed as a nonlinear autoregressive model:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Y_{t+1}=f_\\theta(Y_t,Y_{t-1},\\ldots,Y_{t-L+1})+\\varepsilon_{t+1}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The model is not automatically better than ARIMA or SARIMA. Its advantage appears when nonlinear lag interactions, many covariates, or complex regime-dependent effects are important and enough data are available.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.4 Mathematical form of a multilayer perceptron\n",
        "\n",
        "A feedforward neural network is a composition of affine maps and nonlinear activation functions. Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf h^{(0)}=\\mathbf x.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For layers $\\ell=1,\\ldots,m$, define\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf a^{(\\ell)}=W^{(\\ell)}\\mathbf h^{(\\ell-1)}+\\mathbf b^{(\\ell)},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf h^{(\\ell)}=\\sigma_\\ell(\\mathbf a^{(\\ell)}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a regression forecast, the final layer is often linear:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_\\theta(\\mathbf x)\n",
        "=\n",
        "W^{(m+1)}\\mathbf h^{(m)}+\\mathbf b^{(m+1)}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The full parameter vector is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\theta=\n",
        "\\{W^{(1)},\\mathbf b^{(1)},\\ldots,W^{(m+1)},\\mathbf b^{(m+1)}\\}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Common activations include:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{ReLU}(z)=\\max\\{0,z\\},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\tanh(z)=\\frac{e^z-e^{-z}}{e^z+e^{-z}},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\sigma(z)=\\frac{1}{1+e^{-z}}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The activation function is what makes the model nonlinear. Without nonlinear activations, a composition of affine transformations collapses to a single affine transformation.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.5 Loss functions and empirical risk\n",
        "\n",
        "Let $\\mathcal I_{\\text{train}}$ be the set of training forecast origins. For a multi-output forecast with horizon $H$, the mean squared error objective is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "J(\\theta)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{|\\mathcal I_{\\text{train}}|H}\n",
        "\\sum_{t\\in\\mathcal I_{\\text{train}}}\n",
        "\\sum_{h=1}^H\n",
        "\\left(Y_{t+h}-\\widehat Y_{t+h|t}\\right)^2,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "(\\widehat Y_{t+1|t},\\ldots,\\widehat Y_{t+H|t})=f_\\theta(\\mathbf x_t).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Other losses may be better for different goals:\n",
        "\n",
        "- mean absolute error for robustness;\n",
        "- Huber loss for a compromise between MSE and MAE;\n",
        "- quantile loss for probabilistic forecasting;\n",
        "- cross-entropy for sequence classification;\n",
        "- custom decision loss when underprediction and overprediction have different costs.\n",
        "\n",
        "With $L_2$ regularization, the training problem becomes\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat\\theta\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\arg\\min_\\theta\n",
        "\\left\\{\n",
        "J(\\theta)+\\lambda\\|\\theta\\|_2^2\n",
        "\\right\\}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "In neural-network terminology, $\\lambda\\|\\theta\\|_2^2$ is often implemented as **weight decay**.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.6 Backpropagation as the chain rule on a computational graph\n",
        "\n",
        "Training requires gradients of the loss with respect to all parameters:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla_\\theta J(\\theta).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a one-hidden-layer network,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat y\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\mathbf v^\\top \\sigma(W\\mathbf x+\\mathbf b)+c,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and squared loss\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(\\theta)=\\frac12(\\widehat y-y)^2,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "we can write the computation as\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf a=W\\mathbf x+\\mathbf b,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\mathbf h=\\sigma(\\mathbf a),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\widehat y=\\mathbf v^\\top\\mathbf h+c,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "L=\\frac12(\\widehat y-y)^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The chain rule gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial \\widehat y}=\\widehat y-y,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial \\mathbf v}\n",
        "=(\\widehat y-y)\\mathbf h,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial c}=\\widehat y-y,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial W}\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\left[(\\widehat y-y)\\mathbf v\\odot \\sigma'(\\mathbf a)\\right]\\mathbf x^\\top,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial \\mathbf b}\n",
        "=(\\widehat y-y)\\mathbf v\\odot \\sigma'(\\mathbf a).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Backpropagation is an efficient algorithmic procedure for applying these chain-rule calculations through a large computational graph. It is not finite-difference differentiation, and it is not symbolic simplification. It stores intermediate quantities from the forward pass and reuses them in the backward pass.\n",
        "\n",
        "Gradient descent updates parameters by\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\theta_{k+1}=\\theta_k-\\alpha\\nabla_\\theta J(\\theta_k),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "or, in practice, by a stochastic or mini-batch variant such as Adam or AdamW.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Why this matters for time series\n",
        "For a time-series neural network, the inputs are not independent in time. But once windows are constructed, the training objective is still an empirical risk over many overlapping examples. The validation design must remember where those windows came from.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.7 Interactive demonstration: input and label windows\n",
        "\n",
        "The module below shows how a single observed series is transformed into supervised examples. The blue points form the input window and the orange points form the label window.\n",
        "\n",
        "<div class=\"interactive-card\">\n",
        "  <h3>Interactive Module: Sliding Window Builder</h3>\n",
        "  <p class=\"small-note\">Change the input length, forecast horizon, and window start. The maximum start value is adjusted automatically so the input and label windows always fit inside the simulated series.</p>\n",
        "\n",
        "  <div class=\"controls\">\n",
        "    <label for=\"ch19_input\"><strong>Input length $L$:</strong> <span id=\"ch19_input_value\">24</span></label>\n",
        "    <input id=\"ch19_input\" type=\"range\" min=\"6\" max=\"36\" step=\"1\" value=\"24\">\n",
        "\n",
        "    <label for=\"ch19_horizon\"><strong>Forecast horizon $H$:</strong> <span id=\"ch19_horizon_value\">12</span></label>\n",
        "    <input id=\"ch19_horizon\" type=\"range\" min=\"1\" max=\"24\" step=\"1\" value=\"12\">\n",
        "\n",
        "    <label for=\"ch19_start\"><strong>Window start:</strong> <span id=\"ch19_start_value\">10</span></label>\n",
        "    <input id=\"ch19_start\" type=\"range\" min=\"0\" max=\"84\" step=\"1\" value=\"10\">\n",
        "  </div>\n",
        "\n",
        "  <p id=\"ch19_window_summary\" class=\"small-note\"></p>\n",
        "  <div id=\"ch19_window_plot\" style=\"height:430px;\"></div>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.8 Interactive demonstration: activation functions\n",
        "\n",
        "Neural networks become nonlinear because of activation functions. The module below compares three common choices.\n",
        "\n",
        "<div class=\"interactive-card\">\n",
        "  <h3>Interactive Module: Activation Function Explorer</h3>\n",
        "  <p class=\"small-note\">The activation is applied after an affine transformation. Without it, stacking layers would still produce only an affine map.</p>\n",
        "\n",
        "  <label for=\"ch19-activation-scale\"><strong>Input scale:</strong> <span id=\"ch19-activation-scale-value\">1.00</span></label>\n",
        "  <input id=\"ch19-activation-scale\" type=\"range\" min=\"0.25\" max=\"3.00\" step=\"0.05\" value=\"1.00\" style=\"width:100%;\">\n",
        "\n",
        "  <label for=\"ch19-activation-bias\"><strong>Bias shift:</strong> <span id=\"ch19-activation-bias-value\">0.00</span></label>\n",
        "  <input id=\"ch19-activation-bias\" type=\"range\" min=\"-3.00\" max=\"3.00\" step=\"0.05\" value=\"0.00\" style=\"width:100%;\">\n",
        "\n",
        "  <div id=\"ch19-activation-plot\" style=\"height:430px;\"></div>\n",
        "</div>\n",
        "\n",
        "<script>\n",
        "(function () {\n",
        "  function initCh19ActivationExplorer() {\n",
        "    const plot = document.getElementById(\"ch19-activation-plot\");\n",
        "    const scaleSlider = document.getElementById(\"ch19-activation-scale\");\n",
        "    const biasSlider = document.getElementById(\"ch19-activation-bias\");\n",
        "    const scaleValue = document.getElementById(\"ch19-activation-scale-value\");\n",
        "    const biasValue = document.getElementById(\"ch19-activation-bias-value\");\n",
        "    if (!plot || !scaleSlider || !biasSlider || !scaleValue || !biasValue) return;\n",
        "\n",
        "    const x = Array.from({length:241}, (_, i) => -6 + 12 * i / 240);\n",
        "\n",
        "    function relu(z) { return Math.max(0, z); }\n",
        "    function sigmoid(z) { return 1 / (1 + Math.exp(-z)); }\n",
        "\n",
        "    function update() {\n",
        "      const a = parseFloat(scaleSlider.value);\n",
        "      const b = parseFloat(biasSlider.value);\n",
        "      scaleValue.textContent = a.toFixed(2);\n",
        "      biasValue.textContent = b.toFixed(2);\n",
        "      const z = x.map(v => a * v + b);\n",
        "\n",
        "      const traces = [\n",
        "        {x:x, y:z.map(relu), mode:\"lines\", name:\"ReLU\"},\n",
        "        {x:x, y:z.map(Math.tanh), mode:\"lines\", name:\"tanh\"},\n",
        "        {x:x, y:z.map(sigmoid), mode:\"lines\", name:\"sigmoid\"}\n",
        "      ];\n",
        "\n",
        "      const layout = {\n",
        "        title:\"Activation Functions Applied to $a x + b$\",\n",
        "        xaxis:{title:\"input x\"},\n",
        "        yaxis:{title:\"activation output\"},\n",
        "        margin:{t:70, r:30, b:50, l:60},\n",
        "        legend:{orientation:\"h\", y:-0.2}\n",
        "      };\n",
        "\n",
        "      Plotly.react(\n",
        "        plot,\n",
        "        traces,\n",
        "        layout,\n",
        "        window.TSInteractives ? window.TSInteractives.plotlyConfig : {responsive:true, displayModeBar:true}\n",
        "      );\n",
        "    }\n",
        "\n",
        "    scaleSlider.addEventListener(\"input\", update);\n",
        "    biasSlider.addEventListener(\"input\", update);\n",
        "    update();\n",
        "  }\n",
        "\n",
        "  if (document.readyState === \"loading\") {\n",
        "    document.addEventListener(\"DOMContentLoaded\", initCh19ActivationExplorer);\n",
        "  } else {\n",
        "    initCh19ActivationExplorer();\n",
        "  }\n",
        "})();\n",
        "</script>\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.9 Python example: simulate a nonlinear seasonal time series\n",
        "\n",
        "The following synthetic series contains autoregressive dependence, nonlinear dependence, seasonality, and noise. It is simple enough to understand but nonlinear enough to motivate a neural model."
      ],
      "id": "6d0c078e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-simulate-nonlinear-series\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Synthetic nonlinear seasonal time series for neural forecasting.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "rng = np.random.default_rng(7339)\n",
        "\n",
        "n = 650\n",
        "y = np.zeros(n)\n",
        "\n",
        "for t in range(2, n):\n",
        "    seasonal = 0.45 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * t / 24)\n",
        "    nonlinear = 0.25 * np.tanh(1.5 * y[t - 1])\n",
        "    y[t] = (\n",
        "        0.62 * y[t - 1]\n",
        "        - 0.22 * y[t - 2]\n",
        "        + seasonal\n",
        "        + nonlinear\n",
        "        + rng.normal(0, 0.28)\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "time = np.arange(n)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(9, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(time, y)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"time\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Synthetic nonlinear seasonal time series\")\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-simulate-nonlinear-series",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 19.10 Python example: construct input and label windows\n",
        "\n",
        "The function below transforms a single series into a supervised learning data set. This is the most important preprocessing step for neural forecasting."
      ],
      "id": "3fd9e659"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-window-function\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "def make_windows(series, input_length, horizon):\n",
        "    \"\"\"Return input windows X, target windows Y, and forecast origins.\n",
        "\n",
        "    X[i] contains observations used as input.\n",
        "    Y[i] contains the next horizon observations used as labels.\n",
        "    origins[i] is the last time index included in X[i].\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    series = np.asarray(series, dtype=float)\n",
        "    X, Y, origins = [], [], []\n",
        "    last_start = len(series) - input_length - horizon + 1\n",
        "\n",
        "    for start in range(last_start):\n",
        "        end = start + input_length\n",
        "        X.append(series[start:end])\n",
        "        Y.append(series[end:end + horizon])\n",
        "        origins.append(end - 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "    return np.asarray(X), np.asarray(Y), np.asarray(origins)\n",
        "\n",
        "L = 36\n",
        "H = 12\n",
        "X, Y, origins = make_windows(y, input_length=L, horizon=H)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"X shape:\", X.shape)\n",
        "print(\"Y shape:\", Y.shape)\n",
        "print(\"First forecast origin:\", origins[0])"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-window-function",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-window-visualization\n",
        "#| fig-cap: One input window and its corresponding label window.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "example = 120\n",
        "input_index = np.arange(example, example + L)\n",
        "label_index = np.arange(example + L, example + L + H)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(9, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(time, y, linewidth=1, label=\"full series\")\n",
        "plt.scatter(input_index, y[input_index], label=\"input window\", zorder=3)\n",
        "plt.scatter(label_index, y[label_index], marker=\"x\", s=70, label=\"label window\", zorder=3)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"time\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"A supervised example produced from a time series\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
