      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 19.11 Chronological splitting and scaling\n",
        "\n",
        "A random split is usually invalid for forecasting because it lets future patterns leak into the training set. We split the windowed examples chronologically:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\text{train} \\; \\longrightarrow \\; \\text{validation} \\; \\longrightarrow \\; \\text{test}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Scaling must also be fit on the training period only. If the test period is used to compute the mean or standard deviation, the model has already seen information from the future."
      ],
      "id": "bce92e81"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-split-scale\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "\n",
        "train_end = int(0.70 * len(X))\n",
        "val_end = int(0.85 * len(X))\n",
        "\n",
        "X_train, Y_train = X[:train_end], Y[:train_end]\n",
        "X_val, Y_val = X[train_end:val_end], Y[train_end:val_end]\n",
        "X_test, Y_test = X[val_end:], Y[val_end:]\n",
        "\n",
        "x_scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X_train)\n",
        "y_scaler = StandardScaler().fit(Y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "Xs_train = x_scaler.transform(X_train)\n",
        "Xs_val = x_scaler.transform(X_val)\n",
        "Xs_test = x_scaler.transform(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "Ys_train = y_scaler.transform(Y_train)\n",
        "Ys_val = y_scaler.transform(Y_val)\n",
        "Ys_test = y_scaler.transform(Y_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Number of training windows:\", len(X_train))\n",
        "print(\"Number of validation windows:\", len(X_val))\n",
        "print(\"Number of test windows:\", len(X_test))"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-split-scale",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Scaling leakage\n",
        "Do not call `fit_transform` on the full data set before splitting. For forecasting, preprocessing parameters should be learned from the training period and then applied to validation and test periods.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.12 Python example: baseline and linear window models\n",
        "\n",
        "Before training a neural network, always build baselines. A useful naive multi-step forecast repeats the most recent observed value:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat Y_{t+h|t}=Y_t,\n",
        "\\qquad h=1,\\ldots,H.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "We also fit a ridge regression model on the same input windows. This is a linear benchmark for the neural network."
      ],
      "id": "fee97745"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-baselines\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error\n",
        "\n",
        "naive_pred = np.repeat(X_test[:, -1:], H, axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "ridge = Ridge(alpha=3.0)\n",
        "ridge.fit(Xs_train, Ys_train)\n",
        "ridge_pred_scaled = ridge.predict(Xs_test)\n",
        "ridge_pred = y_scaler.inverse_transform(ridge_pred_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "def forecast_metrics(name, truth, pred):\n",
        "    truth_flat = truth.ravel()\n",
        "    pred_flat = pred.ravel()\n",
        "    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(truth_flat, pred_flat))\n",
        "    mae = mean_absolute_error(truth_flat, pred_flat)\n",
        "    return {\"model\": name, \"RMSE\": rmse, \"MAE\": mae}\n",
        "\n",
        "baseline_results = [\n",
        "    forecast_metrics(\"naive repeat-last\", Y_test, naive_pred),\n",
        "    forecast_metrics(\"ridge window model\", Y_test, ridge_pred),\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "pd.DataFrame(baseline_results)"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-baselines",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 19.13 Python example: train a window-based MLP in PyTorch\n",
        "\n",
        "The MLP below maps an input window of length $L=36$ to a forecast path of length $H=12$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_\\theta:\\mathbb R^{36}\\to\\mathbb R^{12}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The architecture is intentionally small. In a course project, model size should be chosen by validation performance, not by excitement about deep learning."
      ],
      "id": "324a81d3"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-pytorch-mlp-training\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Training and validation loss curves for the window-based MLP.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "import torch\n",
        "from torch import nn\n",
        "\n",
        "torch.manual_seed(7339)\n",
        "torch.set_num_threads(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "Xtr = torch.tensor(Xs_train, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
        "Ytr = torch.tensor(Ys_train, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
        "Xva = torch.tensor(Xs_val, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
        "Yva = torch.tensor(Ys_val, dtype=torch.float32)\n",
        "\n",
        "class WindowMLP(nn.Module):\n",
        "    def __init__(self, input_length, horizon):\n",
        "        super().__init__()\n",
        "        self.net = nn.Sequential(\n",
        "            nn.Linear(input_length, 64),\n",
        "            nn.ReLU(),\n",
        "            nn.Dropout(0.10),\n",
        "            nn.Linear(64, 32),\n",
        "            nn.ReLU(),\n",
        "            nn.Linear(32, horizon),\n",
        "        )\n",
        "\n",
        "    def forward(self, x):\n",
        "        return self.net(x)\n",
        "\n",
        "model = WindowMLP(input_length=L, horizon=H)\n",
        "loss_fn = nn.MSELoss()\n",
        "optimizer = torch.optim.AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3, weight_decay=1e-3)\n",
        "\n",
        "train_losses = []\n",
        "val_losses = []\n",
        "best_state = None\n",
        "best_val = float(\"inf\")\n",
        "patience = 30\n",
        "wait = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "for epoch in range(300):\n",
        "    model.train()\n",
        "    optimizer.zero_grad()\n",
        "    pred = model(Xtr)\n",
        "    loss = loss_fn(pred, Ytr)\n",
        "    loss.backward()\n",
        "    optimizer.step()\n",
        "\n",
        "    model.eval()\n",
        "    with torch.no_grad():\n",
        "        val_loss = loss_fn(model(Xva), Yva).item()\n",
        "\n",
        "    train_losses.append(loss.item())\n",
        "    val_losses.append(val_loss)\n",
        "\n",
        "    if val_loss < best_val - 1e-5:\n",
        "        best_val = val_loss\n",
        "        best_state = {k: v.detach().clone() for k, v in model.state_dict().items()}\n",
        "        wait = 0\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        wait += 1\n",
        "        if wait >= patience:\n",
        "            break\n",
        "\n",
        "if best_state is not None:\n",
        "    model.load_state_dict(best_state)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(train_losses, label=\"training loss\")\n",
        "plt.plot(val_losses, label=\"validation loss\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"epoch\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"scaled MSE\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"MLP training history\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-pytorch-mlp-training",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 19.14 Python example: evaluate the neural forecast\n",
        "\n",
        "We now evaluate on the held-out test period. The test set was not used to fit preprocessing parameters, train the model, or choose the best epoch."
      ],
      "id": "fa9fbe52"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-mlp-test-evaluation\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "model.eval()\n",
        "with torch.no_grad():\n",
        "    mlp_pred_scaled = model(torch.tensor(Xs_test, dtype=torch.float32)).numpy()\n",
        "\n",
        "mlp_pred = y_scaler.inverse_transform(mlp_pred_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "all_results = baseline_results + [\n",
        "    forecast_metrics(\"MLP window model\", Y_test, mlp_pred)\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "pd.DataFrame(all_results).sort_values(\"RMSE\")"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-mlp-test-evaluation",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "A neural model does not have to win every comparison. A strong linear baseline may be difficult to beat when the data-generating mechanism is mostly linear, the sample size is small, or the neural architecture is not tuned. The correct conclusion is not always \"use a larger neural network.\" The correct conclusion is to inspect the error by horizon, validation design, and residual structure."
      ],
      "id": "46350351"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-horizon-errors\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Forecast error by horizon for baseline, linear, and neural models.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "def rmse_by_horizon(truth, pred):\n",
        "    return np.sqrt(np.mean((truth - pred) ** 2, axis=0))\n",
        "\n",
        "horizons = np.arange(1, H + 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(horizons, rmse_by_horizon(Y_test, naive_pred), marker=\"o\", label=\"naive\")\n",
        "plt.plot(horizons, rmse_by_horizon(Y_test, ridge_pred), marker=\"o\", label=\"ridge\")\n",
        "plt.plot(horizons, rmse_by_horizon(Y_test, mlp_pred), marker=\"o\", label=\"MLP\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"forecast horizon\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"RMSE\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Horizon-wise forecast error\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-horizon-errors",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-forecast-path-example\n",
        "#| fig-cap: One test-window forecast path from the MLP and benchmark models.\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "\n",
        "case = 20\n",
        "origin = origins[val_end + case]\n",
        "future_index = np.arange(origin + 1, origin + H + 1)\n",
        "history_index = np.arange(origin - L + 1, origin + 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(9, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(history_index, y[history_index], label=\"history\")\n",
        "plt.plot(future_index, Y_test[case], marker=\"o\", label=\"future observed\")\n",
        "plt.plot(future_index, naive_pred[case], marker=\"o\", label=\"naive\")\n",
        "plt.plot(future_index, ridge_pred[case], marker=\"o\", label=\"ridge\")\n",
        "plt.plot(future_index, mlp_pred[case], marker=\"o\", label=\"MLP\")\n",
        "plt.axvline(origin, linestyle=\"--\", linewidth=1)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"time\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"One multi-step forecast from a held-out test window\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-forecast-path-example",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 19.15 Mini-batches and stochastic optimization\n",
        "\n",
        "The code above used the full training set each epoch. Large neural forecasting problems use mini-batches. If the training windows are\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\{(\\mathbf x_i,\\mathbf y_i):i=1,\\ldots,N\\},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then a mini-batch $B\\subset\\{1,\\ldots,N\\}$ gives the stochastic gradient approximation\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla_\\theta J_B(\\theta)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{|B|H}\\sum_{i\\in B}\\sum_{h=1}^H\n",
        "\\nabla_\\theta\n",
        "\\left(y_{i,h}-f_\\theta(\\mathbf x_i)_h\\right)^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The mini-batch examples can often be shuffled **within the training period** because the model is trained on windows, not by updating a hidden state through the original sequence. However, the train-validation-test split itself should remain chronological."
      ],
      "id": "3c125b6f"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: ch19-dataloader-sketch\n",
        "#| warning: false\n",
        "from torch.utils.data import TensorDataset, DataLoader\n",
        "\n",
        "train_loader = DataLoader(\n",
        "    TensorDataset(Xtr, Ytr),\n",
        "    batch_size=64,\n",
        "    shuffle=True,\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "batch_X, batch_Y = next(iter(train_loader))\n",
        "print(\"mini-batch X shape:\", tuple(batch_X.shape))\n",
        "print(\"mini-batch Y shape:\", tuple(batch_Y.shape))"
      ],
      "id": "ch19-dataloader-sketch",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 19.16 Regularization and early stopping\n",
        "\n",
        "Neural time-series models can overfit badly because overlapping windows create many similar training examples. Common regularization tools include:\n",
        "\n",
        "- small architectures;\n",
        "- weight decay;\n",
        "- dropout;\n",
        "- early stopping based on validation loss;\n",
        "- noise injection or data augmentation when justified;\n",
        "- limiting the input window length;\n",
        "- comparing against simple baselines.\n",
        "\n",
        "Early stopping uses validation loss to choose a training epoch:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat k\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\arg\\min_k J_{\\text{val}}(\\theta_k).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The test set should be used only once at the end.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Many windows do not mean many independent examples\n",
        "If $L=36$ and two adjacent training examples differ by only one time step, the examples are highly overlapping. Neural networks may appear to have a large training set, but the effective amount of independent information may be much smaller.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.17 Neural forecasting workflow\n",
        "\n",
        "A responsible neural forecasting workflow is:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. plot the data and build naive baselines;\n",
        "2. define the forecast horizon and decision metric;\n",
        "3. construct windows without using future information;\n",
        "4. split chronologically into training, validation, and test periods;\n",
        "5. fit scaling transformations on training data only;\n",
        "6. train a small model first;\n",
        "7. monitor training and validation losses;\n",
        "8. compare against naive and linear baselines;\n",
        "9. inspect horizon-wise errors;\n",
        "10. write a diagnostic report describing where the model succeeds and fails.\n",
        "\n",
        "The model is only one part of the forecasting system. The validation design often matters more than the architecture.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.18 AI-assisted modeling activity\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-ai}\n",
        "## AI-assisted study box\n",
        "Ask an AI assistant:\n",
        "\n",
        "> I am training a neural network to forecast a time series using sliding windows. Give me a checklist of possible time leakage sources. For each item, explain how I can test for it in code.\n",
        "\n",
        "Then verify the answer manually. In particular, check whether the assistant remembers that scaling, feature construction, rolling statistics, hyperparameter selection, and validation splits can all introduce leakage.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-ai}\n",
        "## AI-assisted debugging prompt\n",
        "Use the following prompt when your neural model performs too well:\n",
        "\n",
        "> My neural forecasting model has surprisingly low test error. Here is my splitting code, scaling code, and feature construction code. Identify any place where future information may enter the training process. Do not suggest a new architecture until leakage has been ruled out.\n",
        "\n",
        "A suspiciously good forecast is often more dangerous than a bad forecast.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-ai}\n",
        "## AI-assisted mathematical explanation\n",
        "Ask an AI assistant to explain why a linear neural network with no nonlinear activations is equivalent to one linear layer. Then write the proof yourself by composing two affine maps:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "W_2(W_1\\mathbf x+\\mathbf b_1)+\\mathbf b_2\n",
        "=\n",
        "(W_2W_1)\\mathbf x+(W_2\\mathbf b_1+\\mathbf b_2).\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.19 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Using random train-test splits.** Random splits leak future regimes into the training set.\n",
        "2. **Scaling before splitting.** The future test mean and variance should not be used during training.\n",
        "3. **Skipping baselines.** A neural network that cannot beat a naive seasonal forecast is not useful.\n",
        "4. **Confusing many windows with much information.** Overlapping windows are strongly dependent.\n",
        "5. **Using too large a network.** Large networks can memorize local patterns in small time-series data sets.\n",
        "6. **Evaluating only one-step forecasts.** Many applications require horizon-wise multi-step evaluation.\n",
        "7. **Ignoring prediction uncertainty.** A point forecast alone may not support decision-making.\n",
        "8. **Assuming deep learning removes feature thinking.** Calendar effects, known future covariates, and transformations often matter.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.20 Exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Let $f_\\theta:\\mathbb R^L\\to\\mathbb R$ be a one-step neural forecast. Write the empirical MSE objective for forecast origins $t=L,\\ldots,T-1$.\n",
        "2. Show that if every activation function is the identity, then a multilayer feedforward network represents an affine function.\n",
        "3. For $L=24$, $H=6$, and $T=500$, how many supervised windows can be constructed from a univariate series?\n",
        "4. Explain why a random split of sliding windows may produce leakage even if no test target appears explicitly in the training set.\n",
        "5. Modify the Python example so that $H=1$. Compare the MLP with an AR-style ridge model.\n",
        "6. Modify the Python example so that $L=12,24,48$. Which input length gives the best validation loss?\n",
        "7. Replace MSE loss with MAE or Huber loss. How do the forecasts change?\n",
        "8. Add a known seasonal feature, such as $\\sin(2\\pi t/24)$ and $\\cos(2\\pi t/24)$, to the input. Compare performance.\n",
        "9. Use recursive one-step forecasting instead of multi-output forecasting. Compare horizon-wise error curves.\n",
        "10. Write a diagnostic report for the MLP model using a time plot, loss curve, horizon-wise RMSE, and one forecast-path example.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.21 Mini project\n",
        "\n",
        "Choose one real time series and build a neural forecasting pipeline.\n",
        "\n",
        "Your report should include:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. a clear forecasting question and horizon;\n",
        "2. an exploratory plot and at least one seasonality or dependence diagnostic;\n",
        "3. naive and linear baselines;\n",
        "4. a window-based neural network;\n",
        "5. chronological train-validation-test splitting;\n",
        "6. scaling fit on the training period only;\n",
        "7. horizon-wise error analysis;\n",
        "8. a discussion of whether the neural network is justified;\n",
        "9. an AI-assisted critique section where you ask an AI assistant to find weaknesses in your workflow and then verify or reject its suggestions.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 19.22 Checklist\n",
        "\n",
        "Before moving to CNNs, RNNs, LSTMs, and transformers, make sure you can answer the following questions.\n",
        "\n",
        "- What are $L$ and $H$ in a windowed forecasting problem?\n",
        "- What is the difference between sequence-to-one and sequence-to-sequence forecasting?\n",
        "- Why should time-series validation be chronological?\n",
        "- Why should scaling be fit on the training period only?\n",
        "- What baseline did your neural model beat?\n",
        "- Does your model's error increase with horizon?\n",
        "- Does the validation loss suggest overfitting?\n",
        "- Can you explain the model as a nonlinear autoregression?\n",
        "- Can you describe the loss function mathematically?\n",
        "- Can you identify at least three possible leakage sources?"
      ],
      "id": "a5f49d4a"
    }
  ],
